<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="continuous-delivery">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>automation-tooling</domain>
    <summary>Router for CD knowledge cluster. Dispatches to cd-basics or cd-pipelines. Includes triage checklist, CD/CI/CDeployment matrix, DORA targets, and concrete agent prompts.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>continuous-delivery</tag>
      <tag>index</tag>
      <tag>router</tag>
      <tag>deployment</tag>
      <tag>dora-metrics</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
    <updated>2026-05-01</updated>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Continuous Delivery (Index)</title>
    <summary>Router file for the CD knowledge cluster. Dispatches to cd-basics for principles, prerequisites, expand-contract migrations, and phased adoption roadmap; dispatches to cd-pipelines for YAML, deployment strategies (blue-green, canary, rolling), health checks, and monitoring. Reading this index alone is insufficient — always fan out to the correct child after running the triage checklist below.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>CD topics cluster into two distinct concern layers: the conceptual/process layer (what CD is, when it applies, how to adopt it) and the implementation layer (concrete pipeline YAML, rollout strategies, rollback wiring). Merging them produces a file too large to auto-load and too broad to act on. This index keeps routing cheap and lets agents load exactly one focused child.</p>
      <p>Empirical anchor: 2024-2025 DORA reports show elite performers deploy on-demand with under-1-hour lead time and under-15% change failure rate. Teams routinely conflate Continuous Delivery (manual prod trigger) with Continuous Deployment (automatic prod push) and skip the safety nets — this router exists to break that conflation before any pipeline change is written.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Trigger: a user prompt mentions "CD", "continuous delivery", "release pipeline", "deployment automation", "DORA metrics", or "blue-green / canary / rolling" without specifying basics vs. pipeline YAML.</item>
        <item>Trigger: an agent must produce an executive summary of CD using only the Quick Reference and CD vs CI matrix below.</item>
        <item>Trigger: cross-linking another knowledge base (trunk-based-dev, feature-flags, devops-engineer) into a single CD landing page.</item>
        <item>Trigger: auditing CD readiness across multiple services and needing a router to fan out per-service to cd-basics or cd-pipelines.</item>
        <item>Trigger: stakeholder asks "are we doing CD?" — answer requires the matrix here plus a prerequisite check from cd-basics.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Implementation work — open cd-basics or cd-pipelines directly; do not paraphrase from this index.</item>
        <item>Continuous Deployment safety nets (canary analysis, SLO-based rollout gates, automated rollback) — covered in cd-pipelines, not here.</item>
        <item>Team-process change management — Accelerate and The DevOps Handbook are referenced but not unpacked; route to product-operations or pm domains.</item>
        <item>Branching strategy questions — route to trunk-based-dev-principles / trunk-based-dev-patterns.</item>
        <item>Feature-flag system design — route to feature-flags methodology.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Triage Checklist — Run Before Answering">
      <checklist>
        <check>Identify the user's intent: principles/process vs. pipeline YAML vs. metrics dashboard vs. branching strategy.</check>
        <check>Pick exactly ONE primary child file: cd-basics OR cd-pipelines. If both are needed, sequence them — basics first, pipelines second.</check>
        <check>Confirm the team has CI in place (green build on every push). If not, BLOCK CD discussion and route to ci-basics or testing-developer skill first.</check>
        <check>Confirm test coverage exists for the path being delivered. If absent, escalate to testing-developer before continuing.</check>
        <check>Decide whether the request implies Continuous Delivery (manual trigger) or Continuous Deployment (auto). Quote the matrix verbatim if the user used "CD" ambiguously.</check>
        <check>Verify referenced child slugs exist on disk before writing the answer (see Verify section).</check>
        <check>Pair every DORA elite claim with a measurement source (where the metric will be collected from) — never quote elite numbers as targets without instrumentation.</check>
        <check>If recommending Continuous Deployment, confirm canary analysis, SLO gates, and automated rollback are present — otherwise demote recommendation to Continuous Delivery.</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>
    <section name="What is Continuous Delivery">
      <p>Continuous Delivery is the practice of automatically preparing every passing commit for production release. The production deployment itself requires a manual trigger (Continuous Delivery) or fires automatically (Continuous Deployment).</p>
      <list>
        <item>Every commit is releasable: automated testing, feature flags, backward compatibility.</item>
        <item>Deployment pipeline: automated path from commit to production-ready artifact.</item>
        <item>Automate everything: build, test, deploy, rollback.</item>
        <item>Feature flags: deploy code dark; release by toggling, not deploying.</item>
        <item>Backward-compatible migrations: safe database changes across multiple deployments via expand-contract (see cd-basics).</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="CI vs CD vs Continuous Deployment">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always quote this matrix verbatim when explaining the distinction; conflating CD (Delivery) with CD (Deployment) leads teams to enable auto-prod-deploy without the required safety nets.</statement>
        <rationale>Teams commonly believe Continuous Delivery means auto-deploy to production; the matrix makes the manual-trigger distinction explicit and prevents premature auto-deploy adoption.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Build automation: CI yes, CD yes, CDeployment yes.</p>
      <p>Automated tests: CI yes, CD yes, CDeployment yes.</p>
      <p>Deploy to staging: CI no, CD yes, CDeployment yes.</p>
      <p>Production-ready: CI no, CD yes, CDeployment yes.</p>
      <p>Auto-deploy to prod: CI no, CD NO (manual trigger), CDeployment YES (automatic).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="DORA Elite Targets">
      <list>
        <item>Deployment frequency: on-demand, multiple per day.</item>
        <item>Lead time for changes: under 1 hour from commit to production.</item>
        <item>Change failure rate: 0-15%.</item>
        <item>Time to restore: under 1 hour.</item>
        <item>Reliability (added in 2021 DORA report): SLO targets met for the past 30 days.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Deployment Strategies Summary">
      <list>
        <item>Blue-Green: two identical environments, instant cutover. Zero downtime, doubles infrastructure cost. Detail: cd-pipelines.</item>
        <item>Canary: gradual traffic shift (10% then 50% then 100%). Limits blast radius; requires traffic routing and SLO-driven gates. Detail: cd-pipelines.</item>
        <item>Rolling: gradual pod replacement (default Kubernetes). Simple; brief mixed-version window — needs backward-compatible API. Detail: cd-pipelines.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Routing Table — When to Read What">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always route to the most specific child file; never answer implementation questions from this index alone.</statement>
        <rationale>This index is a router; answering from it produces vague bullets that omit prerequisites, migration patterns, and concrete pipeline YAML.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>CD principles, prerequisites, feature flags, expand-contract migrations, DORA targets, adoption roadmap → read cd-basics.</item>
        <item>Pipeline YAML, deployment strategies (blue-green/canary/rolling), health checks, monitoring, rollback → read cd-pipelines.</item>
        <item>Feature flag system design → read feature-flags.</item>
        <item>Branch strategy, trunk-based development → read trunk-based-dev-principles and trunk-based-dev-patterns.</item>
        <item>CI fundamentals (test on every push, green build) → escalate to testing-developer / code-quality skills.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="How-To — Routing Procedure">
      <how-to>
        <step>Read the user prompt and classify: principles, pipeline-YAML, metrics, or strategy.</step>
        <step>Run the Triage Checklist above; abort and reroute if a CI / coverage prerequisite is missing.</step>
        <step>Open exactly one child methodology.xml under solo/dev/automation-tooling/ matching the classification.</step>
        <step>Quote the CI/CD/CDeployment matrix verbatim if the user used "CD" ambiguously.</step>
        <step>Produce the answer from the child file content; reference this index only as a routing breadcrumb.</step>
        <step>Run the Verify section commands to ensure cross-links are not broken.</step>
        <step>Append a one-line "next-step" pointer (e.g., "Open cd-pipelines for the YAML.") so the user can drill down further.</step>
      </how-to>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Integration and Best Practices">
      <section name="Recommended Workflows">
        <list>
          <item>Treat this file as a router. The agent reads the user question, runs the Triage Checklist, consults the routing table, then opens exactly one child file and produces output from that.</item>
          <item>For broad audits (CD readiness across N services), batch: open cd-basics once, score each service against the prerequisite list, then drop into cd-pipelines only for services that need pipeline work.</item>
          <item>Cache the matrix verbatim in the response — never paraphrase it; teams confuse CD with CDeployment when language drifts.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="Agentic Best Practices">
        <list>
          <item>Always answer from the most specific file: cd-pipelines for YAML, cd-basics for principles, feature-flags for release control, trunk-based-dev-* for branching. The index is for routing only.</item>
          <item>Use the CD vs CI vs CDeployment matrix verbatim when explaining the distinction; teams confuse them constantly.</item>
          <item>Pair DORA elite claims with measurement instructions, not aspirational targets — agents that quote the elite numbers without instrumentation create false expectations.</item>
          <item>When linking to Continuous Deployment, note the additional safety bar: automated canary analysis, SLO-based rollout gates, real-time monitoring tied to deploy events.</item>
          <item>Never propose a deployment-strategy change without first checking CI greenness, test coverage, and feature-flag availability for the affected service.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
        <antipattern>
          <description>Agents try to answer implementation questions from this index alone and produce hand-wavy bullets.</description>
          <reason>Force a child-file read; cd-basics and cd-pipelines contain the detail.</reason>
        </antipattern>
        <antipattern>
          <description>Quoting the matrix while skipping prerequisites in cd-basics leads teams to adopt CD without CI or test coverage in place.</description>
          <reason>Always reference cd-basics prerequisites before recommending CD adoption.</reason>
        </antipattern>
        <antipattern>
          <description>Continuous Deployment prompts trigger agents to enable auto-deploy on services that lack canary analysis or rollback.</description>
          <reason>Block auto-deploy until the prerequisites in cd-basics are checked off.</reason>
        </antipattern>
        <antipattern>
          <description>Cross-link rot: agents follow paths to non-existent neighbors.</description>
          <reason>Validate paths with the ls commands in the Verify section before writing the response.</reason>
        </antipattern>
        <antipattern>
          <description>Quoting DORA elite numbers as immediate targets for a team that has not instrumented deploys.</description>
          <reason>Demand fourkeys / Sleuth / LinearB instrumentation be present (or planned) before referencing the elite tier.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section name="Tools and Services">
      <section name="CLI Tools">
        <list>
          <item>gh / glab — inspect deploy events, environments, approvals (github / gitlab CLI).</item>
          <item>dora-team/fourkeys — compute DORA metrics across services (github.com/dora-team/fourkeys).</item>
          <item>cd-cli (homegrown) — wrap children tooling under one entrypoint.</item>
          <item>argocd / fluxcd — pull-based GitOps deploy controllers; surface sync status for the agent.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="Platforms">
        <list>
          <item>Sleuth.io / LinearB (SaaS) — DORA dashboards across services; useful at index level for executive views.</item>
          <item>GitHub Environments / GitLab Environments (SaaS) — approval gates as the CD-vs-CDeployment fulcrum.</item>
          <item>Spinnaker / Harness — opinionated multi-stage CD platforms with built-in canary analysis (route to cd-pipelines for setup).</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <commands>
        <command name="check-cd-readiness">gh api repos/:owner/:repo/actions/workflows --jq '.workflows[] | {name, path, state}'</command>
        <command name="check-environments">gh api repos/:owner/:repo/environments --jq '.environments[] | {name, protection_rules}'</command>
        <command name="check-recent-deploys">gh api repos/:owner/:repo/deployments --jq '.[0:5] | .[] | {ref, environment, created_at}'</command>
        <command name="dora-frequency">git log --since='7 days ago' --pretty=format:'%H %s' -- '*deploy*' | wc -l</command>
        <command name="dora-lead-time">git log --since='7 days ago' --pretty=format:'%h %ar %s' main</command>
        <command name="validate-routing-children">ls skills/faion/knowledge/solo/dev/automation-tooling/cd-basics/methodology.xml skills/faion/knowledge/solo/dev/automation-tooling/cd-pipelines/methodology.xml</command>
        <command name="lint-methodology">python3 scripts/validate-methodology-xml.py skills/faion/knowledge/solo/dev/automation-tooling/continuous-delivery/methodology.xml</command>
      </commands>
    </section>
    <section name="Prompt Template — Routing Decision">
      <prompt purpose="route a CD question to the right child file"><![CDATA[
You are a CD-router agent. Decide which child file answers the user's question.

User question:
"""
{{question}}
"""

Steps:
1. Classify intent: [principles | pipeline-yaml | metrics | strategy | branching | feature-flags].
2. Apply the Triage Checklist (CI present? coverage present? CD vs CDeployment?).
3. Output JSON exactly:
{
  "intent": "<one of the categories>",
  "primary_child": "cd-basics | cd-pipelines | feature-flags | trunk-based-dev-principles | trunk-based-dev-patterns",
  "secondary_child": "<optional second child>",
  "blockers": ["<missing prerequisites>"],
  "matrix_quote_required": true|false,
  "next_action": "open <child>/methodology.xml and answer from there"
}

Do not answer the user's question yet. Only emit the routing JSON.
]]></prompt>
    </section>
    <section name="Template — Executive CD Summary">
      <template path="content/01-overview.xml" purpose="Use as the canonical short-form CD overview when stakeholders need a one-page brief."/>
      <p>When asked for an exec summary, paste the CI/CD/CDeployment matrix verbatim, list the 4 DORA elite targets, list the 3 deployment strategies one-line each, and end with: "For implementation, open cd-pipelines. For prerequisites and roadmap, open cd-basics."</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Verify">
      <verify>
        <step>Run the validator: <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[python3 scripts/validate-methodology-xml.py skills/faion/knowledge/solo/dev/automation-tooling/continuous-delivery/methodology.xml]]></code> and confirm it prints PASS.</step>
        <step>Confirm both child methodologies exist: <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[ls skills/faion/knowledge/solo/dev/automation-tooling/cd-basics/methodology.xml skills/faion/knowledge/solo/dev/automation-tooling/cd-pipelines/methodology.xml]]></code></step>
        <step>Confirm related neighbours exist: <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[ls skills/faion/knowledge/solo/dev/automation-tooling/feature-flags/methodology.xml skills/faion/knowledge/solo/dev/automation-tooling/trunk-based-dev-principles/methodology.xml skills/faion/knowledge/solo/dev/automation-tooling/trunk-based-dev-patterns/methodology.xml]]></code></step>
        <step>If any path is missing, do NOT paper over it from this index — file an issue and route the user to the closest sibling instead.</step>
        <step>After producing the routing decision, double-check the JSON parses: <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[echo "$ROUTING_JSON" | python3 -c "import json,sys; json.load(sys.stdin); print('ok')"]]></code></step>
        <step>Check that the response includes the CI/CD/CDeployment matrix verbatim if the user's prompt used "CD" without qualification.</step>
        <step>Confirm DORA targets are quoted with at least one instrumentation source (fourkeys, Sleuth, LinearB, or git-log heuristic) — never bare numbers.</step>
      </verify>
    </section>
    <section name="References and Related Knowledge">
      <list>
        <item>Jez Humble and David Farley, Continuous Delivery (Pearson, 2010).</item>
        <item>Nicole Forsgren et al., Accelerate (IT Revolution, 2018).</item>
        <item>Gene Kim et al., The DevOps Handbook (IT Revolution).</item>
        <item>DORA: https://www.devops-research.com/research.html</item>
        <item>Martin Fowler, Continuous Delivery: https://martinfowler.com/bliki/ContinuousDelivery.html</item>
        <item>Children: solo/dev/automation-tooling/cd-basics/, cd-pipelines/.</item>
        <item>Related: solo/dev/automation-tooling/feature-flags/, trunk-based-dev-principles/, trunk-based-dev-patterns/.</item>
        <item>State of DevOps Report (DORA 2024/2025) — primary source for elite targets.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
  </content>
</methodology>
